Findings table

| priority | category | issue | why it matters | recommended fix |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| high | conflict | Rule 8 and Rule 14 define overlapping reply-ending requirements without a single precedence rule. Rule 8 says every in-progress substantive reply ends with a status line, while Rule 14 says every substantial reply must end with a `## Next Actions` block, with partially overlapping exceptions. See [.github/copilot-instructions.md](/Users/mac/Desktop/agent-framework-template/.github/copilot-instructions.md#L174) and [.github/copilot-instructions.md](/Users/mac/Desktop/agent-framework-template/.github/copilot-instructions.md#L375). | Agents can comply with both, but the file does not say whether both are always required, in what order, or which one wins when space is tight. That creates avoidable drift in implementations. | Create one “response-shape contract” section. Make Rule 8 define the required visible footer/status pattern, and have Rule 14 only govern decision logic plus a short cross-reference. If both are required, state the exact order explicitly. |
| high | overlap | Checkpointed-task obligations are repeated across Rules 3, 4, 5, 7, 18, 20, and 21. Examples include `Active Task ID` fields, progress receipts, drift packets, handoff packets, allowed-files limits, and closeout boundaries. See [.github/copilot-instructions.md](/Users/mac/Desktop/agent-framework-template/.github/copilot-instructions.md#L41), [.github/copilot-instructions.md](/Users/mac/Desktop/agent-framework-template/.github/copilot-instructions.md#L54), [.github/copilot-instructions.md](/Users/mac/Desktop/agent-framework-template/.github/copilot-instructions.md#L113), and [.github/copilot-instructions.md](/Users/mac/Desktop/agent-framework-template/.github/copilot-instructions.md#L636). | This is the main maintainability risk. Any future change to checkpoint semantics now requires editing many rules, and partial updates will create contradictions again. | Extract a single authoritative “Checkpointed Task Contract” subsection or appendix, then replace repeated lists with short references to that section. Keep local rule-specific exceptions only where they truly differ. |
| high | maintainability | Rule 7 is carrying too many responsibilities: session-state hygiene, rollover, context reset, checkpoint receipts, drift handling, handoff behavior, hard gates, and owner review. See [.github/copilot-instructions.md](/Users/mac/Desktop/agent-framework-template/.github/copilot-instructions.md#L113). | Even though the markdown is valid, the section is hard to scan and harder to modify safely because operational state policy and execution-artifact policy are interleaved. | Split Rule 7 into “Cross-Session State”, “Rollover and Reset”, and “Checkpoint Sync” or move reset/checkpoint mechanics into Rule 18 with Rule 7 focused on `session_state.md` only. |
| medium | conflict | Terminology is inconsistent around execution metadata. Rule 20 defines an `Execution Boundary`, but Rule 27 audits `Rule 9 + EC §1` and says Git policy is “declared in Execution Contract before task starts.” See [.github/copilot-instructions.md](/Users/mac/Desktop/agent-framework-template/.github/copilot-instructions.md#L740) and [.github/copilot-instructions.md](/Users/mac/Desktop/agent-framework-template/.github/copilot-instructions.md#L1187). | `EC §1` / “Execution Contract” is not clearly defined in the file, so the audit section points to a concept name the reader cannot reliably map back to Rule 20. | Standardize on one term. Either rename Rule 20’s block to `Execution Contract` and define sections, or change Rule 27 to say `Execution Boundary` everywhere. |
| medium | format | Rule 21 says “verify all five conditions,” but the readiness table contains four conditions. See [.github/copilot-instructions.md](/Users/mac/Desktop/agent-framework-template/.github/copilot-instructions.md#L797). | This is a small but concrete correctness issue in the document itself. It weakens confidence in a section that is supposed to be procedural and exact. | Fix the count or add the missing fifth condition. |
| medium | overlap | Rules 22, 23, 25, and 26 form one acceptance/evidence/evaluation pipeline, but the lifecycle is split across four distant rules with repeated concepts such as UAC evidence, receipts, and completion claims. See [.github/copilot-instructions.md](/Users/mac/Desktop/agent-framework-template/.github/copilot-instructions.md#L860), [.github/copilot-instructions.md](/Users/mac/Desktop/agent-framework-template/.github/copilot-instructions.md#L941), [.github/copilot-instructions.md](/Users/mac/Desktop/agent-framework-template/.github/copilot-instructions.md#L1057), and [.github/copilot-instructions.md](/Users/mac/Desktop/agent-framework-template/.github/copilot-instructions.md#L1112). | The policy is mostly coherent, but the reader has to reconstruct the sequence manually: define UAC, ensure toolchain, gather evidence, anchor claims, then get independent evaluation. | Group these as an “Acceptance and Closeout” cluster, or add a short lifecycle summary at the start of Rule 22 that points to the exact order of Rules 23, 25, and 26. |
| low | format | The standalone italicized reference lines between Rules 17 and 18 read like floating metadata rather than part of a rule section. See [.github/copilot-instructions.md](/Users/mac/Desktop/agent-framework-template/.github/copilot-instructions.md#L630). | Not broken markdown, but it interrupts flow and looks like an orphaned footer/header fragment. | Move these references to the top intro block, or label them as a small “Core Truth Surfaces” subsection. |
| low | maintainability | Rule 6’s taxonomy table mixes document classes (`TYPE-A/B/C`) with process artifacts (`Progress receipt`, `Drift packet`) under a single `Type` column. See [.github/copilot-instructions.md](/Users/mac/Desktop/agent-framework-template/.github/copilot-instructions.md#L89). | The section is technically readable, but the conceptual model is muddier than it needs to be. Readers cannot tell whether receipts are document types or execution artifacts. | Split into two tables: “Document Classes” and “Execution Artifacts.” Keep the artifact layout example beneath the second table. |

Merge opportunities

- Merge Rule 5 into Rule 15. Rule 5 is mostly a forwarder plus two checkpoint notes.
- Merge the checkpoint-specific repeated lists from Rules 3, 4, 5, and 7 into one canonical checkpoint contract, then cross-reference it from Rules 18, 20, and 21.
- Merge Rule 8 and Rule 14’s output-shape requirements into one reply-format contract.
- Merge Rule 22 and Rule 23 into a tighter acceptance flow, or keep them separate but add a short ordered checklist at the start of Rule 22.
- Cross-reference Rule 25 from Rule 9 and Rule 22 instead of restating receipt/evidence expectations in multiple places.
- Consider moving Rule 26 next to Rules 22-25 so the acceptance pipeline reads in execution order.
- In Rule 6, separate long-lived doc taxonomy from runtime audit artifacts instead of keeping them in one table.

Keep-as-is

- The file no longer appears structurally broken. Headings are continuous from Rule 0 to Rule 27, tables are valid, and code fences are closed.
- Rule 20 is strong and should remain the main posture-setting section. Its execution-boundary block is concrete and actionable.
- Rule 22’s insistence on user-observable acceptance criteria is valuable and should not be weakened.
- Rule 25’s receipt-anchor concept is strong governance and worth preserving.
- Rule 27 is useful as an operational audit lens; it should stay, but its terminology should be aligned with the rest of the file.

Final recommendation

This file is no longer in a broken markdown state, so this is not a formatting-repair job. The highest-value work now is structural consolidation: unify response-shape rules, centralize the checkpointed-task contract, and standardize execution-boundary terminology. After that, split Rule 7 and clean up small correctness issues like the Rule 21 count mismatch. The goal should be to preserve the current governance depth while reducing the number of places a future edit has to touch.
